A lot of people write and complain this isn't a car show anymore.

41:32.292 --> 41:33.566
It is now!

41:34.792 --> 41:38.557
I love this enthusiasm. Why have you painted all yours white?

41:38.557 --> 41:41.542
Because I wanted them to match. I wanted them to be a work of art.

41:41.882 --> 41:45.921
I've got a white garage or "car house" as they're sometimes known.

41:46.205 --> 41:49.538
It's got a white piano in it, right?

41:49.539 --> 41:54.208
That plays itself, and there are these eight beautiful white Farrarris.

41:54.209 --> 41:55.481
And I've got them matching number plates.

41:56.686 --> 42:00.252
Which led you to that auction. When you bid for the Ferrari California.

42:00.253 --> 42:01.841
The James Coburn's car.
- Yes.

42:01.842 --> 42:03.597
This is terribly vulgar.

42:03.598 --> 42:05.419
How much did you pay for that?

42:05.419 --> 42:08.169
It was the most expensive car sold at auction in the world.

42:08.169 --> 42:10.456
When I bought it.
- Last year?

42:10.457 --> 42:13.415
A lot of millions?
- Yes, 12 millions dollars.

42:14.611 --> 42:17.538
How drunk were you?
- I wasn't drunk at all.

42:17.538 --> 42:22.744
The point is, I didn't go to buy the car. I went to buy a poster.

42:22.745 --> 42:23.827
I'm not joking! I'm not joking!

42:23.828 --> 42:25.446
I went to buy a poster, and...

42:25.676 --> 42:28.417
The 250 Spider came up on the stand,

42:28.418 --> 42:30.445
my second favourite car in the world

42:30.445 --> 42:32.915
because it was in my Top Trumps collection.

42:32.916 --> 42:34.049
As simple as that.

42:34.050 --> 42:36.878
Because that how this thing works and that's how life is sometime

42:36.878 --> 42:37.978
I thought I would go for it.

42:37.979 --> 42:40.221
Because I always wanted one. That was the best one in the world,

42:40.221 --> 42:42.407
James Coburn owned it for 28 years.

42:42.408 --> 42:45.561
He bought it because Steve McQueen, he met Steve McQueen in The Great Escape.

42:45.973 --> 42:48.799
Talking about this makes the hairs on the back of my neck stand up.

42:48.800 --> 42:51.101
It's all documented, I've got all the history

42:51.101 --> 42:54.208
and that baby is back in the garage at home.

42:54.209 --> 42:55.782
I show it to as many people as I can.

42:55.783 --> 42:56.535
Unbelievable.

42:56.536 --> 42:59.580
Now. I was listening to you the other day, listen to you everday

42:59.580 --> 43:03.231
whilst stuck in a traffic jam, and you've auctioned

43:03.231 --> 43:05.272
your entire collection of Ferraris,

43:05.273 --> 43:08.246
most of your collections of Ferraris, for Children In Need.
- Yes.

43:08.247 --> 43:09.662
So how does that work?

43:09.663 --> 43:12.567
People ring in and they were bidding?
- Yes.

43:12.568 --> 43:13.984
And then they can drive whichever one they want?

43:13.984 --> 43:18.312
What happen is, we take the seven highest bids on the day

43:18.312 --> 43:22.658
and they spend a four-day tour and during the four days,

43:22.793 --> 43:26.823
each person who's bid the amount of money gets to drive every single car.

43:26.823 --> 43:29.050
Isn't that terrifying from your point of view?

43:29.659 --> 43:32.752
It's only tin and rubber. And I think the great thing about this kind of cars.

43:32.787 --> 43:35.105
If anybody comes round to my house, whether they're fitting a carpet,

43:35.105 --> 43:37.622
do the garden, burgling,

43:38.353 --> 43:41.070
just before you take that, come and have a look at the cars.

43:41.105 --> 43:43.232
I think it's really important to share these cars with people.

43:44.895 --> 43:48.066
You don't know who's bid. You know their names.

43:48.067 --> 43:50.269
You could have any sort of ape turning up.

43:51.085 --> 43:52.818
Well, if you bid...

43:56.661 --> 43:59.436
You've got a book out.
"It's not what you think".

43:59.884 --> 44:01.290
Which is what it's called.
- Yes.

44:01.465 --> 44:04.456
And there's a list of everything at the beginning of every chapter.

44:04.457 --> 44:05.457
Top tens.
- The top tens.

44:05.458 --> 44:07.633
Which is great. A man loves the top tens.

44:07.634 --> 44:08.906
We like to quantify everything.

44:09.057 --> 44:11.739
But this car business, it does seem to me that cars,

44:11.739 --> 44:13.965
you sometimes claim you're not a car man,

44:13.966 --> 44:15.393
but you bloody well are.

44:15.394 --> 44:16.845
No, I'm definitely a car man.

44:16.845 --> 44:21.298
Behind my family, my job, maybe you're not not going to like this

44:21.299 --> 44:25.389
maybe golf, then I am a car man.

44:25.390 --> 44:27.454
Sometimes, if I'm away from home,

44:27.454 --> 44:29.345
the first thing I do, I get back home

44:29.346 --> 44:31.910
and I have to go to garage just to have a smell.

44:31.910 --> 44:34.702
I love it. The smell of petrol and leather,

44:34.702 --> 44:40.099
I love it to death. It's better than stuff I've never tried.

44:42.225 --> 44:43.911
Okay, now.

44:43.911 --> 44:46.228
When I first met you about a million years ago,
- Yes.

44:46.228 --> 44:49.124
you were definitely a Porsche man.

44:49.124 --> 44:51.575
You are having a laugh!
You have 968..

44:51.576 --> 44:54.927
You've lost your mind. You need to go to Venice -

44:55.143 --> 44:57.805
Did you have a 968?
- No.

44:57.806 --> 45:01.766
You did, convertible, Big Breakfast.
- I didn't have 968.

45:01.767 --> 45:05.977
It wasn't 968, cos 968 was Tiptronic and mine was manual.

45:06.012 --> 45:08.287
So it was a 944?

45:08.288 --> 45:12.588
It was a 944 drop top, 19 grand, it was a great car,

45:12.588 --> 45:16.380
but it was dull and boring because it was a Porsche.

45:16.920 --> 45:18.839
Obviously, the big news is,

45:18.839 --> 45:23.298
that Chris Evans -- broadcasting air waves so many years,

45:23.298 --> 45:26.669
is about to take over from the Terry Master.

45:26.669 --> 45:29.969
Has he given you any advice about morning stuff?

45:29.970 --> 45:32.121
How to get up earlier, that's gonna be the number one.

45:32.122 --> 45:36.041
Terry doesn't get up early, Terry gets up at 7 that's not a breakfast show.

45:36.041 --> 45:39.371
What time do you started?
- 7.00am.

45:40.057 --> 45:42.824
It is quite funny. Because you gonna have to pretend to be older than you actually are.

45:42.825 --> 45:45.342
No I'm not, because for somebody at 60.

45:45.343 --> 45:48.156
We had a request the other day, at somebody 60th birthday,

45:48.157 --> 45:50.831
they wanted Van Halen, because that is the music that was around when they were sixties.

45:50.832 --> 45:53.104
So we are okay, I mean there's quality tune about.

45:53.105 --> 45:57.114
You have Brian Johnson on the show, lead of AC/DC. 62 years old.

45:57.115 --> 45:58.656
It's all fine.

45:58.656 --> 46:01.040
It is all fine, we are all going to be, bye-bye generation

46:01.040 --> 46:04.806
we are going to be in our old people's home with Anarchy In The UK in our wheelchairs.

46:04.807 --> 46:08.073
We gonna have a wheelchair and we still gonna be doing that.

46:08.074 --> 46:10.146
I am the antichrist.

46:10.146 --> 46:11.120
Give me a wheelchair.

46:11.121 --> 46:13.683
I don't want any more Gracie Fields, just this.

46:15.824 --> 46:18.840
How did it go for you, out there today on our lap?

46:18.840 --> 46:24.050
Well I did my best, probably the worst weather there has ever been out there.

46:24.075 --> 46:27.485
The Stig, what a lovely man, he couldn't have been nicer,

46:27.485 --> 46:31.509
however, what I have decided to do, I have had a great time.

46:31.897 --> 46:35.147
I thought if I'm going to die, let me die today on this track.

46:35.147 --> 46:41.022
He did actually say, Chris has no sense of self-preservation.

46:42.436 --> 46:47.304
Anybody like to see some of Chris's practices.

46:46.796 --> 46:50.412
Let's have a look at some of these practice thing here.

46:50.413 --> 46:51.413
At the 50 mark, turning,

46:52.436 --> 46:56.100
off the brakes again, brake hard now, into in to second.

46:56.101 --> 46:58.156
This is the hammerhead.

46:58.156 --> 47:01.396
You're going out of control, go out of control.

47:03.648 --> 47:06.171
Nobody has ever spun there before.

47:06.172 --> 47:07.292
That's good.

47:07.293 --> 47:10.264
Watch this.
This is the last corner.

47:10.734 --> 47:11.703
Sideways.

47:11.704 --> 47:13.900
Nobody has ever spun there.
- Sideways at the cruise.

47:13.901 --> 47:17.458
Second last corner, everybody goes here,

47:17.458 --> 47:18.736
I'm impressed.

47:18.737 --> 47:21.280
You never even made it to the corner.

47:21.280 --> 47:23.614
I thought I would just go straight on here.

47:23.615 --> 47:25.459
That was brilliant.

47:25.756 --> 47:29.878
That is good bravery.

47:32.958 --> 47:38.063
But then, the lap happened for real.
Who wants to see it?

47:38.064 --> 47:39.064
Let's have a look.

47:41.670 --> 47:44.694
So you haven't learned your lesson, still going for brute force.

47:44.694 --> 47:47.400
Come on, hello family.

47:48.159 --> 47:49.159
Concentrate, man.

47:49.283 --> 47:52.316
Concentrate on the job in hand, that is wet.

47:52.317 --> 47:54.660
Good, it's Joe 90 mind the wheel.

47:54.661 --> 47:55.905
Cutting across the red and white.

47:55.905 --> 47:59.754
That is slippery. You're looking quite good though.

47:59.754 --> 48:01.858
You have never been good at anything like this in your life,

48:01.859 --> 48:03.629
try and have a go at this.
Come on!

48:03.629 --> 48:07.425
Have you never been good at anything?
- Not like this though.

48:07.709 --> 48:10.669
I'm with you, all sports are impossible.

48:10.670 --> 48:12.789
That is not bad.
- You have to nail hammerhead.

48:13.323 --> 48:18.391
You got to do this, even though your chin does look like a bum!

48:18.391 --> 48:20.719
This is Hammerhead, do we gonna get around this time?

48:20.720 --> 48:22.645
We have put cones out now when it's rain

48:22.646 --> 48:26.128
so Jonathan Ross doesn't get lost if he comes back,

48:26.510 --> 48:29.104
you're in the white lines, that looks slow but important for a quick time.

48:29.104 --> 48:30.518
Aim for the cameraman.

48:30.519 --> 48:31.257
Aim for the cameraman.

48:31.258 --> 48:32.258
Here the cameraman.

48:32.259 --> 48:33.259
Bad karma.

48:33.260 --> 48:36.417
Because I missed the gear aiming for the cameraman.

48:36.418 --> 48:39.990
There he is,
he getting a bit tired now.

48:41.317 --> 48:42.530
That's looking good.

48:42.531 --> 48:46.228
The smell of the clutch. Mmmm.

48:46.229 --> 48:48.368
But does it smell of victory?

48:48.368 --> 48:52.005
I'm being a bit chicky, I'm being a whussy into the final bend.

48:52.006 --> 48:53.073
Come on now!

48:53.073 --> 48:57.381
Cut the corner, just a bit. That's the trick. That's good.

48:57.827 --> 49:01.191
That's quite a lot. This one, cut it a lot.

49:02.069 --> 49:07.769
So an entirely new way across the line.

49:07.869 --> 49:12.390
Here we are. There's the board.

49:12.391 --> 49:13.694
There is the board.

49:13.694 --> 49:17.024
Where do you think? Obviously we will give you a wet lap there.

49:17.024 --> 49:19.123
We will put Chris Evans "wet" on it.

49:19.124 --> 49:20.969
Where do you think you have come?

49:20.969 --> 49:25.512
I don't think it's that impressive, but I did, I promise you I try my best,

49:25.512 --> 49:29.036
but I'm not gonna lean forward, I will try to be cool.

49:29.037 --> 49:31.269
We never had a guest who manage to stay just like that.

49:31.270 --> 49:34.658
I know, I tell you my heart is racing.

49:35.173 --> 49:40.881
You did it in one minute, quicker than Terry Wogan was.

49:41.342 --> 49:46.321
You are already the new fastest Radio Two breakfast show host we have ever had.

49:46.321 --> 49:47.703
In the last 40 years.

49:49.851 --> 49:55.104
You did it in one minute, forty.
- That's good.

49:55.105 --> 49:56.625
Eight point one.

49:56.625 --> 50:05.054
For a wet lap that's the third- fastest wet lap we have ever had.

50:05.687 --> 50:07.032
There's your ex.

50:07.033 --> 50:08.337
I'm just above her,

50:08.338 --> 50:10.528
but I'm not on top of her, just above her.

50:11.734 --> 50:12.461
Cos she's my ex.

50:12.462 --> 50:15.148
But we were accused of favouritism with her by David Tenant,

50:15.148 --> 50:17.531
who said that we only allowed her to cut corner

50:17.532 --> 50:19.707
because she was wearing a see-through top.

50:19.708 --> 50:22.202
And he was quite right of course.
- Completely right.

50:22.203 --> 50:26.560
But you cut corners as well.
- Next time I'm gonna wear a see-through top.

50:27.133 --> 50:30.435
Ladies and gentlemen, Chris Evans. Best of luck.

50:32.345 --> 50:34.640
The new morning man.

50:34.641 --> 50:36.848
That is a good time, be proud of that.

50:41.118 --> 50:44.876
Earlier on in the show, we explained that Lancia,

50:44.876 --> 50:47.775
the greatest car company in the world,

50:47.776 --> 50:51.813
and just because of a few problems with rust 30 years ago,

50:51.813 --> 50:54.875
they are not available in the UK any more.

50:55.122 --> 50:57.739
The thing is though, as Jeremy as been finding out,

50:57.739 --> 51:01.817
you can still get one, sort of.

51:04.926 --> 51:09.926
This is a Lancia Stratos, except for one small thing,

51:09.927 --> 51:10.927
It isn't.

51:13.438 --> 51:16.532
It wasn't made in the 1970s in Italy,

51:16.532 --> 51:19.162
in fact, I don't know where it was made.

51:19.163 --> 51:21.544
In a shed in Nuneaton, probably.

51:23.319 --> 51:26.085
This, you see, is a kit car.

51:26.086 --> 51:30.191
Either you can pay someone to build it for you,

51:30.191 --> 51:34.140
or you can make it at home yourself, with a hammer.

51:35.037 --> 51:39.737
Apparently, if you're fairly competent that would take about 300 hours,

51:39.231 --> 51:44.869
obviously it would take me about 300 years, which is a very long time.

51:44.869 --> 51:50.230
But, there is an upside, an original Stratos would cost

51:50.230 --> 51:52.351
100,000 pounds, maybe more,

51:52.352 --> 51:56.399
that is 13,000 pounds.

52:01.413 --> 52:06.966
In theory that makes this the Hawk HF, the bargain of the century.

52:06.966 --> 52:11.450
The body is absolutely identical to the original,

52:11.451 --> 52:14.994
all the panels are completely interchangable.

52:16.473 --> 52:20.260
The interior too would be familiar to Lancia fans.

52:22.204 --> 52:26.238
The pedals are nowhere near where the bottom of my legs are.

52:26.512 --> 52:31.036
The steering wheel is perilously close to where my testis used to be,

52:31.036 --> 52:35.389
before the seatbelt jammed them up into my lungs.

52:35.493 --> 52:38.475
The gear lever acts like one of Bugs Bunny's ears,

52:38.476 --> 52:42.157
and one of the switches on the dashboard operates a fire extinguisher,

52:42.157 --> 52:45.702
since I don't know which one it is, I dare not touch any of them.

52:46.568 --> 52:50.575
The wiper has gone upside down,

52:50.575 --> 52:55.244
that wouldn't actually clear the rain from the window.

52:55.245 --> 52:57.744
Then there was a big noise.

53:00.270 --> 53:03.159
Wait a minute, what the hell? What was that?

53:03.160 --> 53:05.497
The front left brake had jammed on.

53:05.941 --> 53:10.471
I got to get this in to a workshop. Come on, come on.

53:11.048 --> 53:14.640
I took the car to Nigel, the resident mechanic at our track,

53:14.640 --> 53:17.570
and greeted him in the usual fashion.

53:17.571 --> 53:19.308
Have you got a hammer?

53:22.212 --> 53:26.780
That is scalding hot, as we can see on the thermal-images camera.

53:30.286 --> 53:33.338
He has just gone to answer the phone now.

53:33.339 --> 53:36.270
While we wait, I suppose I should explain

53:36.271 --> 53:40.251
the 13,000 pounds doesn't include the cost of an engine,

53:40.251 --> 53:41.551
you have to get one yourself.

53:41.551 --> 53:44.834
And you have a choice of two, you can either get Fiat's twin-cam,

53:44.835 --> 53:47.414
that you can buy used these day for about 5p,

53:47.415 --> 53:51.442
or for 600 quid, you can get the engine I have in this.

53:51.685 --> 53:55.644
Use this handle which is disguised as a spoiler to get the back up,

53:55.645 --> 53:59.806
and there you are Alfa's brilliant 3 litre V6.

54:00.467 --> 54:04.841
This actually produces more power than the Ferrari engine Lancia used.

54:05.374 --> 54:09.605
And with it the Hawk is faster, when it is working,

54:09.606 --> 54:13.057
which it will be, eventually.

54:17.237 --> 54:20.409
It is mended. Now I'm going to get back in.

54:20.409 --> 54:24.477
Which is a surprisingly elegant process if you're a mouse.

54:24.478 --> 54:25.960
You simply get one...

54:25.961 --> 54:28.195
No, that's not good.

54:28.195 --> 54:32.112
You sort of get over this roll bar, like this.

54:32.112 --> 54:36.924
Then you get your head in, it's probably easier to detatch your head first,

54:36.924 --> 54:39.600
and put it back on in the car.

54:40.644 --> 54:41.962
There we are. Whenever there, and

54:41.963 --> 54:45.240
Over there!
And then..

54:45.240 --> 54:48.980
You might want to cut the camera for this bit.

54:50.932 --> 54:53.757
I had intended at this point to check out the performance,

54:53.757 --> 54:59.642
but after the brake problem I had rather lost my nerve.

55:03.871 --> 55:07.891
0-60 takes less than five seconds

55:07.891 --> 55:14.399
and what I'm not going to do now is see where that acceleration stops.

55:14.660 --> 55:21.662
I really don't want to travel at 150mph in a car built in a shed by a man I have never met.

55:22.828 --> 55:24.435
This is 90 perhaps,

55:24.711 --> 55:27.278
that's, the wiper has gone.

55:28.569 --> 55:30.492
That is an important consideration,

55:30.492 --> 55:34.594
you have to bear in mind if you are thinking of buying a used kit car.

55:34.594 --> 55:35.750
You have to ask,

55:35.751 --> 55:40.137
was it built fastidiously by James May over a period of

55:40.137 --> 55:45.777
many hundreds of years, or was it built by a spanner, with a hammer?

55:47.845 --> 55:52.337
I mean, would you buy a kit car that I had built?

55:56.193 --> 55:58.612
Having chickened on the max speed run,

55:58.612 --> 56:04.260
I decided not find out what it is like flat out through the corners.

56:04.804 --> 56:07.297
Here we go, I'm going in,

56:07.298 --> 56:10.946
and here I am cornering not at all flat out.

56:12.011 --> 56:14.897
60, that's fine.

56:14.898 --> 56:18.707
Brakes, all three and three quarters of them are very squirrelly.

56:18.992 --> 56:22.007
The steering is very heavy, a lot of body roll.

56:22.453 --> 56:23.453
There we are.

56:24.260 --> 56:26.801
I think that's probably enough cornering now,

56:26.801 --> 56:28.910
we have done that, tick.

56:31.494 --> 56:36.159
Certainly then, the Hawk is only as good as the bloke who put it together.

56:36.159 --> 56:40.387
You will spend more time under it than in it, for example.

56:42.207 --> 56:46.843
I'm not going to pretend it is as good as an original Stratos either,

56:46.844 --> 56:55.213
but the same reason that a postcard of the Mona Lisa is not as good as Leonardo's.

56:55.683 --> 56:58.843
But one day your car will be working

56:58.508 --> 57:03.233
and you will see a reflection of yourself in a shop window as you go by,

57:03.233 --> 57:08.137
and trust me on this, that's gonna feel good.

57:08.137 --> 57:11.613
Because critically this looks like a Stratos.

57:11.614 --> 57:17.218
If we're honest, that's all we really want.

57:33.009 --> 57:36.033
I would like to build a kit car like that,

57:36.034 --> 57:37.984
cos I think it would be very therapeutic.

57:37.985 --> 57:39.054
It would be.

57:39.055 --> 57:42.813
You know what I mean. It is more satisfying to have something you have made yourself?

57:43.605 --> 57:45.848
I don't even like to eat a sandwich I have made myself,

57:45.848 --> 57:49.157
because it always has blood in it and bits of my fingers.

57:49.158 --> 57:50.158
But anyway.

57:50.525 --> 57:54.888
We must now find out how fast this car goes round our track,

57:54.888 --> 57:59.192
and of course that means handing it over to our tame racing driver.

57:59.192 --> 58:03.304
Some say his new Christmas range of fragrances,

58:03.305 --> 58:07.806
includes the great smell of Wednesday,

58:07.806 --> 58:11.475
and that he was turned down for the job of EU President,

58:11.475 --> 58:16.022
because his face is just too recoginsable.

58:16.023 --> 58:19.218
All we know is he's called The Stig.

58:20.152 --> 58:21.981
He's off, there he goes.

58:21.982 --> 58:24.031
I say listen to that noise.

58:24.031 --> 58:30.140
The Alfa V6 sounds, if anything, even better than the Ferrari V6.

58:30.297 --> 58:33.147
That's fantastic sound.

58:33.148 --> 58:35.147
What's happening here?

58:35.678 --> 58:38.052
Is he looking for the stereo, no,

58:38.053 --> 58:41.727
Stiggy what's gone wrong? He's broken down.

58:41.727 --> 58:44.570
How authentic is that?

58:44.571 --> 58:48.243
This is a scene familiar to any Lancia owner,

58:48.243 --> 58:51.582
look at him walking off, completing his journey on foot.

58:51.583 --> 58:54.267
There he is, not across the line.

58:54.268 --> 58:55.485
Now, okay.

58:55.716 --> 58:58.605
There is no way we were going to allow

58:58.606 --> 59:01.247
our first-ever DNF (Did Not Finish)

59:01.247 --> 59:04.032
